==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[carefull]] (obsolete)

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|careful|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|carful|lang=ang}}, {{term|cearful|ċearful|careful, anxious, curious, troubled|lang=ang}}, equivalent to {{suffix|care|ful|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈkɛːfəl/}}
* {{audio|en-us-careful.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{obsolete}} Full of [[care]] or [[grief]]; [[sorrowful]], [[sad]].
#* '''1485''', Sir Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book V:
#*: ‘Alas,’ sayde Sir Cadore, ‘now '''carefull''' is myne herte that now lyeth dede my cosyn that I beste loved.’
# {{obsolete}} Full of [[cares]] or [[anxiety]]; [[worried]], [[troubled]].
#*'''1590''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''The Faerie Queene'', III.1:
#*:Where through long watch, and late daies weary toile, / She soundly slept, and '''carefull''' thoughts did quite assoile.
# Having care (for); [[attentive]] to [[potential]] [[danger]], [[error]] or [[harm]]; [[cautious]].
#: ''He was a slow and '''careful''' driver.''
# [[conscientious|Conscientious]] and [[painstaking]]; [[meticulous]].
#: ''They made a '''careful''' search of the crimescene.''

